Now we need:

BFS = Visit level by level

This is arguably the most important graph traversal for interviews

DFS vs BFS
DFS

Go as deep as possible.

Possible order:

0 1 3 4 2
BFS

Visit level by level.

Order:

0 1 2 3 4

What Data Structure Do We Need?

For DFS:

Stack (implicitly through recursion)

For BFS:

Queue

Because:

First node discovered
=
First node processed

FIFO.


BFS Template

void bfs(int start, List<List<Integer>> graph){
    boolean[] visited = new boolean[graph.size()];
    Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();

    q.offer(start);

    visited[start] = true;

    while(!q.isEmpty()){
        int node = q.poll();
        System.out.print(node+" ");
        for(int neighbor : graph.get(node)){
            if(!visited[neighbor]){
                visited[neighbor] = true;
                q.offer(neighbor);
            }
        }
    }
}


void bfs(int start,
         List<List<Integer>> graph)
{
    boolean[] visited =
        new boolean[graph.size()];

    Queue<Integer> q =
        new LinkedList<>();

    q.offer(start);

    visited[start] = true;

    while(!q.isEmpty()) {

        int node = q.poll();

        System.out.print(node + " ");

        for(int neighbor : graph.get(node)) {

            if(!visited[neighbor]) {

                visited[neighbor] = true;

                q.offer(neighbor);
            }
        }
    }
}



Why mark visited BEFORE putting into queue?

Correct:

visited[neighbor] = true;
q.offer(neighbor);

Not:

q.offer(neighbor);
visited[neighbor] = true;

Reason:

If multiple nodes point to the same neighbor, you may enqueue it multiple times before it's marked visited.

That's why BFS is used for:

Shortest path in unweighted graphs
Rotting Oranges
Word Ladder
Minimum moves problems
Minimum steps problems